post_text:
Some Prep required for The Frozen T! The way it works:

1st- Find a t-shirt, soak it with water, place in freezer overnight. Folding is recommended- but you could ball it up or do whatever you see fit. (tip- make it a bigger shirt than you might normally wear so it can more easily go over your clothing)
2nd- Take the shirt out of the freezer and get ready to show some grit (because these are challenging to unfold)
3rd- Put some fun music on in the background and see how long it takes you to unfold the shirt and get it on.
Ways to modify this activity you may ask! Try a sock or two if putting things over your shoulders isn't the jam.

1st- Find a t-shirt, soak it with water, place in freezer overnight. Folding is recommended- but you could ball it up or do whatever you see fit. (tip- make it a bigger shirt than you might normally wear so it can more easily go over your clothing)
2nd- Take the shirt out of the freezer and get ready to show some grit (because these are challenging to unfold)
3rd- Put some fun music on in the background and see how long it takes you to unfold the shirt and get it on.
Ways to modify this activity you may ask! Try a sock or two if putting things over your shoulders isn't the jam.

post_text: Check out these awesome prototypes from 5th grade Inquiry class! Students were given the challenge of helping Ms. Do increase her energy throughout the day. They went through the design thinking process (Empathize, Define, Ideate, Prototype, Test) to create a lightweight, portable, lunchbox fanny pack featuring a water bottle holder and cell phone and walkie talkie clip-ons.

post_text: At Rainier Prep, our goal is to give ALL students a choice in their education, challenged learning, and a pathway towards college. In 5th grade, students visit a college or university to see firsthand what their future can look like. For 2016-2017, our 5th graders visited University of Washington campus and toured some of the facilities. #tbt #rainierprep #mission

post_text: Yesterday was all smiles at Rainier Prep. We've finished our first year of serving students in the Highline area. There is a long road still to go, but we couldn't be prouder of what has been accomplished this year. Here are some photos from our last day of our first year together.

post_text: #tbt to when Rainier Prep was still a dream. Thank you to all of our families and supporters who have made our school a reality. We are about to wrap up our first year and we are forever grateful to everyone that played a part.

post_text: For the end of the year, 6th grade math students have been working on a really "sweet" project. They were instructed to design a candy then, calculate the costs to make it and market it to our 5th grade math students. Yesterday, 6th graders got the chance to "sell" their product to our 5th graders. At the end of the class, 6th graders calculated their profits and discussed the feedback they received from their customers.

post_text:
One of our Rainier Prep families had their home destroyed by a fire on Friday, May 6. They lost everything - clothes, appliances, bedding, even their beloved dog.

We are working to raise money to help them get through this tough time. Funds will go to help them buy extra school clothes and provide for essentials like food and laundry.

We so appreciate anything you can do to help. No amount is too small to make a difference!

post_text: In 5th grade science, we are currently in the middle of some engineering challenges. Using the design thinking model (see http://dschool.stanford.edu/dgift/ for more information), we first tested and built paper airplanes. Now, we are working on marshmallow catapults from a number of different supplies. We will soon be moving on to begin our end-of-year science projects.

post_text: 5th and 6th grade students have been tracking the work of the International Space Station, following both the return of astronaut Scott Kelly from Expedition 46 and then the launch of Expedition 47. Who would have known that an OWL (Rainier Prep's mascot) would have accompanied the launch? Check out the later portion when you can mark the change into microgravity: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lTUrSs0TU2s&sns=em.

post_text: In Computer Science, students are learning about algorithms (the directions a computer follows to accomplish tasks). So far, students have written clear algorithms on how to make a peanut butter and jelly sandwich and how to program another student to stack cups. Make sure to ask your student about their algorithms, they are a neat way to apply real life to our lessons about computer programming!
